---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import { withBase } from "../../utils/url";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Troubleshooting"
  description="Common dbt-burla issues and fixes."
  lede="Something broke. Start here before opening an issue — most problems are one of the patterns below."
  prev={{ title: "Configuration reference", href: withBase("/docs/configuration/") }}
>
  <h2>"Could not find adapter type burla_*"</h2>
  <p>
    <code>pip install "dbt-burla[&lt;warehouse&gt;]"</code> didn't complete, or you're in a
    different virtualenv than dbt itself. Verify:
  </p>
  <Code code={`python -c "from dbt.adapters.burla_duckdb import Plugin; print(Plugin)"`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>"IndentationError: unexpected indent" during a Python model</h2>
  <p>
    dbt emits compiled code with leading whitespace; dbt-burla strips this automatically. If you're
    seeing this, you're on a very old version — upgrade.
  </p>

  <h2>"The `burla` client isn't installed"</h2>
  <p>
    <code>pip install burla</code> (should be pulled in automatically). Or set
    <code>burla_fake: true</code> in your profile to run Python models in-process.
  </p>

  <h2>"Burla cluster unreachable at ..."</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><code>burla login</code> was run and credentials are in <code>~/.config/burla/</code>.</li>
    <li><code>burla_cluster_url</code> in your profile matches your cluster.</li>
    <li><code>BURLA_CLUSTER_DASHBOARD_URL</code> env var isn't set to something stale.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>A quick sanity check:</p>
  <Code code={`python -c "from burla import get_cluster_dashboard_url; print(get_cluster_dashboard_url())"`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>"Python model must return a pandas DataFrame; got ..."</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Returning a <code>list</code> or <code>dict</code> — wrap with <code>pd.DataFrame(...)</code>.</li>
    <li>Returning a Polars / pyarrow object — convert first: <code>df.to_pandas()</code>.</li>
    <li>Forgetting the <code>return</code> statement.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>"Model `X` referenced upstream relation `...` which was not pre-loaded"</h2>
  <p>dbt didn't include the relation in the compiled refs/sources dict. This usually means:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>You're using a non-standard <code>dbt.ref()</code> pattern (e.g., constructing the name dynamically).</li>
    <li>There's a ref that exists in dbt's DAG but isn't reachable by your model's <code>depends_on</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>"Catalog Error: Table with name X__dbt_tmp does not exist"</h2>
  <p>
    You're on an old version of dbt-burla that hadn't shipped its custom DuckDB table
    materialization. Upgrade to <code>&gt;=0.1.0</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Python model runs forever / hangs on Burla</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The Burla cluster is cold-starting workers (first run takes longer).</li>
    <li>Your <code>burla_image</code> is large and being pulled.</li>
    <li>Your <code>model()</code> is doing a synchronous network call without a timeout.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Set <code>burla_timeout_s</code> on the model to fail fast instead of hanging.</p>

  <h2>CI pytest fails with "ResourceWarning: unclosed file"</h2>
  <Code code={`[tool.pytest.ini_options]
filterwarnings = [
    "ignore::ResourceWarning",
    "ignore::pytest.PytestUnraisableExceptionWarning",
]`} lang="toml" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />
  <p>These come from dbt-core's own log file handling, not your code.</p>

  <h2>Snowflake: "100078 (22000): Binding data in type (...) is not supported"</h2>
  <p><code>write_pandas</code> can't handle every pandas dtype. Convert to str/int/float before returning:</p>
  <Code code={`df["my_col"] = df["my_col"].astype(str)
return df`} lang="python" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>BigQuery: "Access Denied" during load_table_from_dataframe</h2>
  <p>
    Your service account needs both <code>bigquery.dataEditor</code> and
    <code>bigquery.jobUser</code> on the target dataset. <code>dbt debug</code> doesn't catch this
    because it only tests SELECT permissions.
  </p>

  <h2>Still stuck?</h2>
  <p>
    Open an issue at
    <a href="https://github.com/Burla-Cloud/dbt-burla/issues">github.com/Burla-Cloud/dbt-burla/issues</a>
    with: <code>dbt --version</code>, full <code>dbt run --debug</code> output, your Python model
    (redacted if needed), and warehouse variant.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
